# Coding Style Standards

## Universal Rules

### Naming
- Variables/functions: descriptive, verb-noun for functions (`getUserById`, not `getUser`)
- Booleans: `is`, `has`, `can`, `should` prefix (`isLoading`, `hasError`)
- Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`
- Avoid abbreviations unless universally known (`id`, `url`, `ctx` OK; `usr`, `val` not OK)

### Functions
- Single responsibility: one function, one job
- Max 30 lines (if longer, decompose)
- Max 3 parameters (use object for more)
- Pure functions preferred (no hidden side effects)

### Files
- Max 300 lines per file
- Group related functions together
- Exports at the bottom or as named exports at declaration

### Error Handling
- Never swallow errors silently
- Always log with context: `logger.error('Failed to fetch user', { userId, error })`
- Use typed error classes for domain errors
- Return `Result<T, E>` or throw — pick one pattern per module

### Comments
- No comments explaining WHAT the code does — code should be self-evident
- Comments explain WHY (business logic, workarounds, constraints)
- TODO comments must include: `// TODO(author): description — issue #123`

## TypeScript Specific
- Prefer `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions/intersections
- Avoid `any` — use `unknown` and narrow
- Use strict mode
- Explicit return types on public functions

## Anti-Patterns
- God objects/functions (do too much)
- Deeply nested callbacks (prefer async/await)
- Mutable default parameters
- Boolean parameter flags (use separate functions or enums)
